<subSubSection box="[199,1268,1110,1135]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,390,1206]" box="[199,1268,1110,1135]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,333,1111,1135]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is descriptive for the subapical group of spines on the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,390,1206]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1147,1171]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species has a unique aedeagal, subapical lateral lobe adorned with setae which will separate it from all other known species.
</paragraph>
